21 to: (1) impose a similar fee if the county in which the city is located has created
22 such an enterprise fund; (2) deposit the fee into the enterprise fund; and (3) use the
23 money collected from the fee to take certain measures to conserve the endangered
24 or threatened species or subspecies. (NRS 268.4413, 268.4415). Sections 3.3, 3.7
25 and 3.9 of this bill allow the money collected from such fees to also be used for the
26 establishment of plans and programs for the conservation of the habitat and
27 ecosystems in certain areas or zones. Sections 3.3 and 3.7 require any such fee
28 collected to be based upon an economic analysis of the cost to carry out such a plan
29 or program for habitat and ecosystem conservation. Section 3.3 also authorizes a
30 board of county commissioners that imposes such a fee to adjust the fee for
31 inflation beginning in Fiscal Year 2026-2027.
32 Existing law requires, subject to certain exceptions, sheriffs, county recorders
33 and county auditors, county clerks, county assessors and county treasurers to keep
34 open the county office and branch offices, if any, on all days except Sundays and
35 nonjudicial days from 9 a.m. to 12 p.m., and on all days except Sundays,
36 nonjudicial days and Saturdays from 1 p.m. to 5 p.m. Existing law also authorizes
37 the board of county commissioners of any county to designate or authorize
38 deviation from the days and hours, but requires each office to be kept open for not
39 less than 40 hours during each week. (NRS 245.040) Existing law establishes that
40 the county treasurers are tax receivers for the county. (NRS 361.475) Section 3.5 of
41 this bill provides that the county office and branch offices, if any, of the county
42 treasurer may not close earlier than 5 p.m. on any business day but may close later
43 than 5 p.m.
44 Existing law requires the tax receiver of the county to mail notice of delinquent
45 taxes to certain persons. The notice of delinquency must state certain information
46 including that if the amount of delinquent taxes is not paid, the tax receiver will, at
47 5 p.m. on the first Monday in June of the current year, issue a certificate
48 authorizing the county treasurer to hold the property. (NRS 361.5648) Section 4 of
49 this bill provides instead that the notice of delinquency must state that if the amount
50 of delinquent taxes is not paid, the tax receiver will, at the close of business of the
51 tax receiver of the county on the first Monday in June of the current year, issue a
52 certificate authorizing the county treasurer to hold the property.
53 Existing law requires the tax receiver to make out a trustee’s certificate that
54 describes each property on which delinquent taxes, penalties, interest and costs
55 have not been paid. The trustee’s certificate authorizes the county treasurer to hold
56 each property for a certain period of time. (NRS 361.570) When the time allowed
57 by law for the redemption of a property described in a certificate has expired and no
58 redemption has been made, the tax receiver who issued the certificate is required to
59 execute and deliver to the county treasurer a deed of the property. Upon obtaining
60 such a deed, the county treasurer is required to hold the property in trust until it is
61 sold or otherwise disposed of. Existing law provides that during certain periods or
62 not later than 5 p.m. on the third business day before the day of the sale by a county
63 treasurer, certain persons are entitled to have the property reconveyed upon the
