81 provides the county treasurer with an affidavit that meets certain requirements.
82 Existing law requires the superintendent of schools in a school district in this
83 State which has more than 100,000 pupils enrolled in its public schools (currently
84 the Clark County School District) to assign a school associate superintendent to
85 oversee one or more local school precincts. (NRS 388G.620) Existing law
86 prescribes the duties of a school associate superintendent, including requiring a
87 school associate superintendent to provide a report in person, not less than
88 quarterly, to the governing body of each city and county within which a local
89 school precinct to which he or she is assigned to oversee is located. (NRS
90 388G.630) Section 7 of this bill eliminates the requirement to report to a county.
91 Exiting law authorizes a board of county commissioners to grant a franchise to
92 construct, install, operate, and maintain street railways, electric light, heat and
93 power lines, gas and water mains and telephone lines, among certain other things.
94 (NRS 709.050) Any person or entity desiring a franchise is required to file an
95 application in writing with the board of county commissioners wherein the
96 franchise is to be exercised. (NRS 709.060) Notice of such an application is
97 required to be given at the next regular meeting of the board and is required to be:
98 (1) published once each week for 4 consecutive weeks in a newspaper of general
99 circulation published in the county, subject to certain exceptions; and (2) posted in
100 three public places nearest where the application will take effect, and if more than
101 one unincorporated town is affected, posted in three public places in each of the
102 unincorporated towns. (NRS 709.070) Section 8 of this bill revises such
103 requirements to post the notice from three places to one place if more than one
104 unincorporated town is affected by reducing the postings required in public places
105 in each of the unincorporated towns.
